<font color="#FF0000">RIGHT AND WRONG</font><br>
<tt>Wed Jul 23  4:29:40 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I didn't kill any people... human beings, in Viet Nam.  But, I did kill alot of Dinks, Slopes, V.C., Cong, Gooks, Charlies, NVA, targets, objectives, etc.  Of course the depersonalization of Vietnamese (or any group of people) greatly facilitates the killing of them.  Too bad the facade doesn't last.  It is a sad confession to admit (years later) to the killing of people, especially children.<br>
Anger, fear, hatred, ignorance, greases the rails for the taking of life.  My question is:  What assuages the guilt?<br>
It does not appear that fault finding, denial, numbing or disassociation works.  You can't blame the ignorant enlisted men, the dumbass sergeants or the stupid officers.  It seems that you have to blame yourself.<br>
Combatants struggle to justify the death of the enemy because of the death of friends.  On the surface it may seem a practical ploy, but beneath the surface it is actually two sets of sad circumstances that compound to plague the survivor.  All the reasons why I killed people seem to support me and abandon me with great fecundity.  I am tossed back and forth on a sea of clarity and doubt.  I hope that each of you have some success in resolving your own trauma in your own way.  You may be infuriated by the words of others and you may be soothed by the words of some.  Take that which is good for you... and leave the rest behind.  Share your thoughts with your brothers, but leave them to judge for themselves about how they feel.
<p><code>-- eramon@edumaster.net  (Edward Ramon) </code><p>


